    <title>Combined summary - Proposal: Force to do nothing for first 9 minutes to save 90% of mining energy</title>
    <updated>2023-06-14T21:56:50.517502+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2021-May/018942.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The issue of energy consumption in Bitcoin mining has been a topic of discussion among the Bitcoin community. Some miners use excess waste energy such as hydropower, while others do not. This leads to a significant share of total energy usage by the network. The carbon footprint of Bitcoin is not as alarming as its energy usage implies since renewable, near-free waste energy helps keep it more green. However, there are concerns about the efficiency paradox and proof of memory fallacy in the process. To address energy consumption issues, some members propose encouraging users to allow only "green miners" to process their transactions and certifying green miners with cryptographic certificates of conformity. However, this proposal risks centralization and undermines the use of proof-of-work. Another proposed solution is to eliminate the need for miners to continue mining for nine minutes after the last block was found. This would incentivize miners to create chips that are idle for 50% of the time and work harder during the remaining 50%, requiring them to buy twice the chips to use the same amount of power. Two possible solutions to prevent pre-mining in the nine-minute window are a global network timer or making mining jobs before nine minutes have a higher difficulty.However, there are concerns about the economic incentive for miners not to draw power when idling and whether it is technically possible to completely power down mining rigs during the cool-down period. Additionally, some members disagree with the concept of carbon credits and argue that such efforts are not necessary or beneficial for Bitcoin's adoption. Finding a working solution could help address the energy concerns of the industry without compromising robustness. Luke Dashjr, a Bitcoin developer, responded to a query on reducing block time in Bitcoin while maintaining security. He acknowledged that increasing security is inevitable and proposed using dRNG, a universal clock, and cryptographic measures to ensure safe mining of blocks. The proposal suggested starting the run for the next coinbase at zero seconds and ending it after 600 seconds with no significant changes if started 540 seconds later but must finish in 60 seconds. The idle time would be nine minutes, which wouldn't affect the 60-second block time. Dashjr appreciated the suggestion and stated that it was ten times harder than ten times softer. He clarified that his previous response was not pointing fingers at Musk and that they were trying hard to make Bitcoin more efficient than any other system, even though they are still working on it. The Bitcoin community has been discussing various proposals to address the issue of energy consumption in Bitcoin mining. One proposal suggested introducing green miner certifications, while another involved delaying mining for nine minutes after a block is found to prevent pre-mining. There are concerns about the feasibility of these proposals and the potential for centralization. A discussion on the bitcoin-dev mailing list explored various proposals to address energy consumption in Bitcoin mining, including certifying "green" miners and allowing only them to process transactions. Other proposals included implementing a global network timer or increasing the difficulty of mining jobs before nine minutes have passed.The ongoing tension between environmental concerns, decentralization, and commercial incentives in the Bitcoin ecosystem is evident. While there are challenges to implementing some of these proposals, the thread emphasizes the importance of considering environmental concerns in the development of blockchain technology. They also raise questions about the security and efficiency of current approaches to Bitcoin mining. The email exchange between Luke Dashjr and ZmnSCPxj discussed proof-of-work and the need for it to create a universal clock that anchors Bitcoin to reality.Overall, finding a working solution could help address the energy concerns of the industry without compromising robustness. The email thread provides a comprehensive overview of the different proposals and considerations related to the issue of energy consumption in Bitcoin mining.</summary>
